Gas prices, in particular, are rising especially fast, reaching $4.25 a gallon on Wednesday, up from about $2.86 per gallon last March. That means filling a 20-gallon tank right now costs $85, up from $57.20 last year at this time.

Not only do they spend a larger share of their income meeting basic needs, they tend to have less savings to help cushion the blow of higher prices.

column5: With pressure to contain inflation mounting, the Fed may raise interest rates faster than it currently predicts, and further depress economic growth in 2023.

column5: With fewer people getting sick, there should be more workers in the transportation sector (truckers and dock workers, for instance)  helping to get goods from producers to consumers.

column1: Analysis: Sidney Poitier left behind a legacy of landmark roles, but some smaller gems as well - CNN
column5: Sidney Poitier left behind a legacy of landmark performances, from his Oscar win for "Lilies of the Field" to the Oscar-winning "In the Heat of the Night," the latter coming in a year, 1967, that also saw him star in "To Sir, With Love" and "Guess Who's Coming to Dinner."

column1: 'Cyrano' review: Peter Dinklage stars in a musical film that doesn't hit enough of the right notes - CNN
column5: "Cyrano de Bergerac" has been the model of a tragic love triangle for 125 years, often imitated but seldom equaled. The play turned movie under many different guises now adds a film version of the musical, "Cyrano," which provides a fine showcase for Peter Dinklage in a different take on the tortured hero but doesn't hit enough high notes to distinguish its unstained plume.

column1: 'The Adam Project' review: Ryan Reynolds comes back from the future in a 'Free Guy' reunion for Netflix  - CNN
column5: Reuniting star-producer Ryan Reynolds and director Shawn Levy after their winning collaboration on "Free Guy," "The Adam Project" has the generic feel of a project created by committee, combining action, humor and smart-alecky one-liners in a way that's at best aggressively okay. That's probably enough for Netflix coming off a success with Reynolds in "Red Notice," but like the film's plot, this amounts to rehashing history.

column1: 'Scream' review: Courteney Cox, David Arquette, and Neve Campbell reunite with a new cast to refresh the formula - CNN
column5: Always meta in its nods to the genre's quirks, the latest "Scream" is so self-referential as to risk swallowing its own tail. Yet this quarter-century-later "requel" (a term specifically explained in the movie) turns out to be a great deal of fun, cleverly wedding familiar faces with new stars in what isn't exactly a remake or reboot but rather plays like a refresh.

column1: 'Marry Me' review: Jennifer Lopez and Owen Wilson star in a 'meet dumb' rom-com - CNN
column5: Designed to showcase Jennifer Lopez playing a character that could hardly be called a reach, "Marry Me" trades in the "meet cute" rom-com formula for "meet dumb." Lopez still gets ample opportunities to sing a hummable soundtrack, but even within the genre's parameters, the silly premise deals the movie a blow from which it never entirely recovers.

column1: 'The Power of the Dog' and its Globes win show that the awards power is in streaming - CNN
column5: The Golden Globes were reduced to a footnote this year -- chased from TV and their usual NBC showcase by questions about the organization's membership and its integrity, relegated to announcing winners Sunday by Twitter and press release.

column1: As 'Obi-Wan Kenobi' heads to Disney+, just remember: It's Han Solo's fault - CNN
column5: Obi-Wan Kenobi is coming to streaming, as practically anyone with an internet connection knows by now. But is that the ideal venue for a project based on a beloved original "Star Wars" character? And while he might insist "It's not my fault!," how much of the blame goes to Han Solo?

column1: 'The Dropout' review: Amanda Seyfried stars in Hulu's eye-opening take on Elizabeth Holmes and Theranos - CNN
column5: Elizabeth Holmes has been a source of fascination for many since glimpsing the husky-voiced, wide-eyed persona she affected in Alex Gibney's documentary "The Inventor: Out for Blood in Silicon Valley." Amanda Seyfried nails all of that in "The Dropout," a slick Hulu docuseries devoted to Holmes' rise and Shakespearean fall, as well as the gender dynamics at play throughout.

column1: 'Bel-Air' review: 'The Fresh Prince' goes down a dark path in a Peacock drama that's better than it has any right to be - CNN
column5: Nobody asked for a dark, dramatic reimagining of "The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air," which makes the new series fitting that description, "Bel-Air," better than it has any right to be. Premiering Super Bowl Sunday on NBC's streaming service Peacock, the opening episodes establish a catchy beat, with the main question being how long they can sustain it.

column1: 'Super Pumped: The Battle for Uber' review: Joseph Gordon-Levitt and Kyle Chandler star in Showtime's latest tech titan takedown - CNN
column5: A cross between "The Social Network" and "Billions," "Super Pumped: The Battle For Uber" hails from the producers of the latter, drawing extra zest from all the tech CEOs represented in this fun, fact-based tale of greed, high-stakes corporate chess and frat-boy excess. With Joseph Gordon-Levitt and Kyle Chandler anchoring the cast, it's well worth hopping aboard.

column1: 'The Andy Warhol Diaries' review: Netflix's Ryan Murphy-produced docuseries gives the artist another 395 minutes of fame - CNN
column5: Andy Warhol was such a distinctive figure -- cutting across the worlds of art, media and pop culture -- that a docuseries about his life could hardly be boring, and "The Andy Warhol Diaries" isn't. But this six-part Netflix production does unfold at a languid, almost-hypnotic pace, while employing AI technology to create Warhol's voice reading his words from the great beyond, which is as oddly creepy as that sounds.

column1: 'The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel' season 4 review - CNN
column5: Season 4 of the Amazon series picks up with the stand-up comic, two years after a strong Season 3. Mrs. Maisel is back on the road and in the spotlight.

column1: 'The Gilded Age' review: Julian Fellowes' sprawling new drama shines as an American version of 'Downton Abbey' - CNN

column5: The James Webb Space Telescope successfully unfurled its 70-foot sunshield on Tuesday. This critical milestone is one of several that must occur for Webb to function properly in space, and it's one of the most challenging spacecraft deployments NASA has ever attempted.

column1: Pittsburgh boom on New Year's Day was an exploding half-ton meteor, NASA says - CNN
column5: A meteor exploded in the atmosphere with a blast equivalent to 30 tons of TNT, NASA said on Monday. The sounds were heard in Pittsburgh a few minutes before 11:30 a.m. on Saturday.

column1: The United Nations plans to update space law after over 50 years of no updates - CNN
column5: The UN created a working group last month to assess potential threats in space and provide recommendations of responsible behaviors in space.

column1: Meteor showers, eclipses, full moons: All of the reasons to look up in 2022 - CNN
column5: The new year is sure to be a sky-gazer's delight with plenty of celestial events on the calendar. Total lunar eclipses, a multitude of meteor showers and supermoons will light up the sky in 2022.

column1: Quadrantid meteor shower kicks off the new year 2022 - CNN
column5: The new year kicks off with the Quadrantid meteor shower, which is expected to peak in the overnight hours from Sunday to Monday.

column1: This year, NASA will launch a mission to a valuable, unexplored world - CNN
column5: This week, learn about NASA's upcoming mission to an unexplored world, meet a digitally "unwrapped" mummy, explore a Neanderthal mystery, uncover why winter is vanishing, get to know the multitude of new species found in 2021, and more.

column1: 10 memorable moments from past nominations - CNNPolitics
column5: Supreme Court confirmation hearings were first televised, gavel-to-gavel, when Sandra Day O'Connor appeared before the Senate Judiciary Committee in 1981.

column1: Biden's strategy with Putin is decades in the making - CNNPolitics
column5: Joe Biden always says foreign relations is about relationships, and he's been developing the one he has with Vladimir Putin for two decades.

column1: New York mayor signs fire safety order after fatal Bronx fire - CNN
column5: New York Mayor Eric Adams signed an executive order on fire safety Sunday, more than two months after the fatal Bronx apartment building fire that left 17 people dead.

column1: Obamacare is gradually becoming a fact of American life - CNNPolitics
column5: Russia's assault on Ukraine has united America's political parties, as war abroad often does. It's more surprising to see diminishing conflict on a hot-button domestic issue -- but recent developments at both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue tell that story on health care.

column1: Opinion: Russian forces 'clearly have very poor standards,' Gen. Petraeus says - CNN
column5: Retired Gen. David Petraeus, who commanded US forces in the Iraq and Afghanistan wars, says the Russians are facing a Ukraine military that is exceptionally determined, surprisingly capable and innovative, and one that is fighting on its home territory for its very survival, writes Peter Bergen.

column1: Opinion: Madison Cawthorn's ridiculous attack on Zelensky - CNN
column5: Rep. Madison Cawthorn is paying for his unforced error and proving how difficult it is to play Trump-style politics. It turns out there's more to it than simply flinging nasty rhetoric and sitting back to gloat while others cry foul, writes Michael D'Antonio.

column1: Don Young, Alaska Republican and Dean of the House, has died - CNNPolitics
column5: US Rep. Don Young, a Republican of Alaska and the dean of the House, has died, his office said in a statement Friday. He was 88.

column1: Why the US has taken so few refugees from Ukraine - CNNPolitics
column5: More than 3 million Ukrainians have fled their country since Russia's invasion, with nearly 2 million pouring into neighboring Poland and hundreds of thousands going to other nearby countries. But very few have come to the US. It's a story of red tape and a broken immigration system.

column1: GOP backlash grows over Madison Cawthorn's Zelensky insult - CNNPolitics
column5: When House Republicans gathered on the baseball field Friday morning for their weekly practice, members were abuzz about one topic: Rep. Madison Cawthorn.

column1: Opinion: Trump's 'America First' policy is dead - CNN
column5: If the last two years have shown us anything, it's that America's strength depends on its international alliances, writes Julian Zelizer.

column1: Analysis: Ketanji Brown Jackson hearings to spotlight Supreme Court's rightward trajectory - CNNPolitics
column5: Judge Ketanji Brown Jackson, a groundbreaking nominee, appears before senators Monday for a seat on a Supreme Court that itself has been moving in reverse.

column1: How to watch the confirmation hearings for Judge Ketanji Brown Jackson - CNNPolitics
column5: Confirmation hearings for the Supreme Court nomination of Judge Ketanji Brown Jackson will begin Monday, with Democratic leaders setting a goal of reaching a final Senate vote by early April.

column1: Ketanji Brown Jackson: American Bar Association rates Biden Supreme Court nominee 'well qualified' - CNNPolitics
column5: The American Bar Association on Friday rated Judge Ketanji Brown Jackson as "well qualified" -- its highest rating -- to serve on the US Supreme Court, ahead of her confirmation hearings next week.

column1: How Judge Ketanji Brown Jackson handled Trump and executive privilege cases  - CNNPolitics
column5: Judge Ketanji Brown Jackson has already ruled in epic battles between Congress and former President Donald Trump, rebuffing efforts to shield White House testimony and records.

column1: Ginni Thomas attended the January 6 rally before the Capitol attack. Here's what we know - CNNPolitics
column5: Virginia "Ginni" Thomas' attendance at the January 6, 2021, rally that preceded the violent attack on the US Capitol has touched off a series of questions about the connection between her activism and the work of her husband, Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas. Here's what you need to know.

column1: Ginni Thomas acknowledges she attended January 6 rally but played no role in planning it - CNNPolitics
column5: Conservative activist Virginia "Ginni" Thomas said in an interview published Monday that although she attended a rally on January 6, 2021, she "played no role" in planning the events that day and that she doesn't involve her husband, Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas, in the political work she does pushing conservative causes.

column1: Texas Supreme Court further limits challenges to state's restrictive abortion law - CNNPolitics
column5: The Texas Supreme Court on Friday issued a ruling that effectively foreclosed the last avenue abortion clinics had to challenge the state's six-week limit on abortions in their current federal litigation.

column1: Murkowski on tough Supreme Court choice: 'This is a different game' - CNNPolitics
column5: Last year, Sen. Lisa Murkowski was one of just three Republicans who voted to elevate Judge Ketanji Brown Jackson to the second most important court in the country. Now, in the middle of an election year, she is faced with a new choice: Promoting her to the highest court in the land.

column1: Opinion: The conditions are ripe for peace in Ukraine - CNN
column5: Russia and Ukraine have been talking, but negotiations would benefit from a leader such as President Joe Biden facilitating the process, Nick Dowling writes. Strong US leadership is essential to the cause of peace, he says.

column1: Opinion: What 'WeCrashed' and 'The Dropout' tell us - CNN
column5: Shows like 'The Dropout,' 'WeCrashed' and 'Super Pumped' are part of an office culture canon that stretches from Herman Melville's 'Bartleby, the Scrivener' to 'The Office,' writes Nicole Hemmer. In their explorations of fraud and workplace abuse, these shows also critique the new economy -- even as they remind us there's no escape from it.

column1: Opinion: Our educational shortcomings drive anti-AAPI sentiment - CNN
column5: Two years ago, the World Health Organization declared Covid-19 a pandemic, marking the beginning of a public health crisis as well as a wave of hate toward Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders (AAPIs). Falsely blamed for the global spread of the virus, the AAPI community has been subjected to violent attacks over and over.

column1: Opinion: The only way to guarantee nuclear weapons are never used - CNN
column5: The world is shocked by the violence in Ukrainian cities besieged by Russian forces, as they suffer under indiscriminate mortar, bomb and missile attacks. But these horrors could lead to something far worse -- escalation to nuclear war.

column1: Opinion: The country where 30 farmers die each day - CNN
column5: India needs far more than agricultural reform, writes Gunisha Kaur. Officials can begin by destigmatizing and decriminalizing suicide, by sincerely committing to collecting accurate data on suicide attempt and mortality, and by devoting resources to support the mental health needs of India's farmers and their families.

column1: Opinion: For pregnant women, war is a particular kind of hell  - CNN
column5: Searing images and horrific aftermath of the bombing of a maternity hospital in Mariupol, Ukraine underscore a tragic reality, writes Jill Filipovic: War is hell for everyone it touches, but women of reproductive age often experience war differently than men do.

column1: Opinion: Putin is calling in favors from Syria and Africa. It's a dangerous move - CNN
column5: Russia says nearly 16,000 foreign volunteers are ready to fight on their side -- many from the Middle East and Africa, where Putin has invested in bolstering governments and military actors. It makes the picture in Ukraine messier -- and more dangerous, writes Naureen Chowdhury Fink.

column1: Opinion: As a child of war, I know what the Ukrainians are going through - CNN
column5: In the early morning of February 24 in New York, hours after Russia started firing missiles near Kyiv, a tweet from The Economist read "In parts of Ukraine, people woke to the sound of sirens and took to their basements; elsewhere some knelt on the streets to pray." If Twitter existed nearly four decades ago, the tweet would have just as accurately described 1980s Tehran.

column1: Opinion: Putin's bombs aren't weakening Ukraine's resolve to fight - CNN
column5: Hospitals, schools and apartment buildings were wrecked, as the civilian death toll mounted. Yet there's no sign the carnage is weakening Ukraine's resolve to fight. Studies of earlier air wars suggest they can strengthen resistance to an attacker.

column1:
Opinion: The one leader who can bring Americans together
 - CNN
column5: Frida Ghitis writes that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky's speech to Congress on Wednesday, in addition to being emotionally searing and extraordinarily powerful, energized support for Ukraine's defense against Russian President Vladimir Putin's war machine and reverberated across the US.

column1: Opinion: Why the US is flirting with authoritarians in countering Putin - CNN
column5: Aaron David Miller writes that while President Joe Biden is standing up to Russian President Vladimir Putin, he's courting authoritarians elsewhere to help American interests like oil and stability.

column1: Whose side is Tucker Carlson on? (Opinion) - CNN
column5: Dean Obeidallah writes that Tucker Carlson's pro-Russian and pro-Putin comments on Fox News in the wake of the invasion of Ukraine makes some wonder who's side he's on. Carlson's comments are so extreme, a recently leaked memo from the Kremlin even asks state media to highlight his show.

column1: Opinion: Florida and Texas can't outlaw my family - CNN
column5: As a trans woman, I am not an emblem of liberal ideology. Nor does my mere existence or presence equate to "sexual instruction" or an effort to "promote a lifestyle," writes Claire McCully. These Florida and Texas laws are an effort to demonize and exclude LGBTQ people from American life. So let us dispense with the fabricated political villain of "transgenderism," and focus instead on reality.

column1: Opinion: Biden and Harris are missing a big opportunity on Ukraine crisis - CNN
column5: Mark Hetfield, president and CEO of HIAS, writes that President Joe Biden and Vice President Kamala Harris are falling short when it comes to addressing the surge of Ukrainian refugees. They should welcome Ukrainians into the US, instead of leaving Europe to contend with the issue.

column1: Opinion: Good news from state judges on gerrymandering - CNN
column5: David Daley writes that in the wake of the bloodbath of partisan gerrymandering, state courts have played an important role in protecting fair districts.

column1: Opinion: Trump must think Russia's invasion of Ukraine is a joke - CNN
column5: Before he entered politics, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky was a professional comedian. Former US President Donald Trump, on the other hand, just plays a bad one at GOP gatherings.

column1: Opinion: Mike Pence is no profile in courage - CNN
column5: Despite former Vice President Mike Pence's attempts to distance himself from former President Donald Trump, Peter Bergen writes that if Pence thinks this will give him a significant leg up over Trump, he has misjudged both the former president and his supporters.

column1: Opinion: Trump documents allegedly claimed his apartment was nearly three times larger than it is - CNN
column5: Michael D'Antonio writes __hat before he became president and started espousing lies about the 2020 election, Donald Trump was a kind of business illusionist whose stock-in-trade allegedly included shifting claims of wealth. Now, thanks to the New York Attorney General, accountability may be at hand.

column1: Opinion: Joe Biden is not failing or flailing - CNN
column5: President Biden's first year in office had its shortcomings, but CNN's senior political analyst Kirsten Powers writes that Biden's presidency is not failing or flailing.

column1: Opinion: What's behind the Hillary Clinton '24 talk - CNN
column5: The most telling thing about a potential Hillary Clinton run in 2024 isn't whether she'll actually do it -- it's in the reactions to the rumors, Michael D'Antonio writes.

column1: Opinion: How the Biden administration can ensure mask access to all Americans - CNN
column5: By distributing high-quality masks directly to the public where they are at, we can maximize protection against the SARS-CoV-2 virus -- balancing equitable access and effective use for all, write Emmeline Ha and Miriam Bukhsh.

column1: Opinion: What 2020's pro-Trump phony electors means for 2024 - CNN
column5: Robert Alexander writes that slates of phony electors from seven states were sent to then-Vice President Mike Pence in an effort to persuade him to discard the legitimate slates of electors he received -- an alarming, albeit unsuccessful, attempt to upend the 2020 presidential election results, and one requiring immediate remedy to avoid repetition in 2024.

column1: Opinion: I was the kid who stayed silent in college - CNN
column5: "It's not about having students, faculty and staff who can recite chapter and verse about the importance of free speech law -- but have little understanding about who on campus feels most compelled to self-silence and why," writes Issac Bailey about self-censorship in college campuses.

column1: Opinion: The March Madness shot that broke our hearts and the real tragedy that followed - CNN
column5: I love March Madness for all the reasons any sports fan loves the tournament, writes Michael Croley, but as I've gotten older, I know that I love the tournament because of these memories and how it kept me close to my brother and our father.

column1: Opinion:  Why 'Turning Red' gives me hope - CNN
column5: Portraying the Asian diaspora as perpetual foreigners fuels anti-Asian hate, writes Vanessa Hua. She says that's why "Turning Red" -- a powerful rebuke to stereotype, released just before the one-year anniversary of the Atlanta spa killings -- gives her hope.

column1: Opinion: It's time to end the 'spring forward' and 'fall back' tired tradition - CNN
column5: Editor's Note: On Tuesday, the Senate passed the Sunshine Protection Act, which would make Daylight Saving Time permanent in the US.

column1: Opinion: We can't ignore the darker sides of global unity on war in Ukraine - CNN
column5: Peniel E. Joseph examines racial bias in coverage of Russia's invasion on Ukraine in historical context and says it's erased the experience of Black and brown people attempting to flee Ukraine, while reinforcing toxic assumptions about who deserves empathy when facing the perils of war.

column1: Opinion: What happened when smoking was banned in American Indian casinos - CNN
column5: American Indian tribes are joining the effort across the nation to ban smoking in casinos, write Patricia Nez Henderson and Catherine Saucedo. Smoke-free casinos are feasible and profitable.

column1: Opinion: This is no time to drop the ball on Covid-19 - CNN
column5: The failure to include a $15.6 billion pandemic aid package in the omnibus spending bill the House passed on Wednesday is a collective mistake that could come back to haunt us.

column1: Opinion: What conversion therapy cost me  - CNN
column5: Conversion therapy is immensely detrimental and costly in countless ways, writes Garrard Conley, who underwent the practice. "My parents say they would give anything to take back what happened to our family, to reverse the harmful effects of conversion therapy. If only they could."

column1: Opinion: What Brittney Griner's quiet face is saying to the world - CNN
column5: WNBA star Brittney Griner's identity as a Black gay woman athlete facing the Russian legal system is a precarious one, and as the war intensifies and diplomatic options wane, Americans must not look away, writes historian Peniel E. Joseph. He says Griner is now one of the quiet faces of a human rights tragedy unfolding before the eyes of the world.

column1: Opinion: Florida officials are harming children in their bid to 'protect' them - CNN
column5: The recently-passed "Don't Say Gay" bill in Florida is the kind of law that no decent parent would support, says Jill Filipovic, and it comes just as Florida health authorities are recommending against Covid-19 vaccines for healthy kids. Florida Republicans claim that they want to protect the rights of parents -- but they seem awfully eager to go out of their way to hurt kids, she argues.

column1: We redefined Blackness as a world and a gift - CNN
column5: Black history is not about saving America or White people, writes Danté Stewart. White people may have made Blackness a curse and a sin but we redefined Blackness as a world and a gift. Black history is about us.

column1: Opinion: Women's soccer settlement is a landmark win for fairness - CNN
column5: Female athletes continue to face opponents on the field and off, constantly told they aren't good enough or strong enough, are dull to watch, celebrate too much when they win, and cry too much when they lose. But a $24 million settlement between the US Women's National Team (USWNT) and the US Soccer Federation (USSF), announced in a court filing Tuesday, is a reminder that the bottom line continues to be clear: empower women's sports to get results, but don't wait for results to invest in women's sports.

column1: Opinion: Why Wordle was perfect for this moment - CNN
column5: Nicole Hemmer puts the Wordle craze in context, explaining why it works so well in our late-pandemic moment but also why it reflects familiar historical patterns of anxiety in American culture around enjoying games and pastimes for pure pleasure.

column1: Opinion: The price Vladimir Putin will pay - CNN
column5: While NATO countries are strengthening defenses on the alliance's eastern flank and the West is imposing severe sanctions, none are intervening directly in Ukraine's defense. So the key question is: What, if any, is the long-term price Putin will pay? One outcome thus far: nearly worldwide condemnation of Russia for its president's attack on Ukraine and a wave of sympathy for the people of Ukraine.

column1: Opinion: A liberal city's wake up call - CNN
column5: "Fellow-citizens, we cannot escape history," President Abraham Lincoln wrote in 1862 as the Civil War raged. Lincoln's words stand out on Presidents Day weekend, when history is being made from Beijing to Ukraine to the US. The uses and misuses of history are at the root of so many struggles playing out right now.

column1: Opinion: Marjorie Taylor Greene's blunder sums it up - CNN
column5: Greene's "gazpacho police" reference came at a head-spinning moment, when hyperpartisan politics and the long-running pandemic have produced a cavalcade of misinformation, disinformation, ignorance, conspiracy theories and self-defeating protests.

column1: Opinion: Neil Young put his finger on America's big divide - CNN
column5: Young's request to take his music off Spotify because of Covid-19 misinformation spread on its platform shows that the battle lines over truth and falsehood aren't just cutting across the political sphere, they are dividing people in media, music and sports.

column1: Opinion: Is mud in Putin's forecast? - CNN
column5: When the snow melts in the spring, fields can get so muddy in the plains of Eastern Europe that Russians have a word for it: Rasputitsa, or "the season of bad roads." Analysts believe that if Putin launches an invasion of Ukraine, it will come before the spring thaw.

column1: Opinion: One big problem in Joe Biden's first year - CNN
column5: Minutes after Joe Biden placed his hand on a five-inch thick family Bible and took the oath of office last January, he promised to focus on uniting America to overcome its challenges, but that goal has proved elusive in his first year in office.

column1: Opinion: This is the revelation America is still waiting for - CNN
column5: One year after the insurrection at the US Capitol, January 6 -- both the day and the historical forces that undergird it -- continues to imperil American democracy, while the world struggles to confront the ways Covid-19 is still destabilizing our lives, writes Jane Greenway Carr. She curates the week in commentary from CNN Opinion contributors on these topics and others, including Novak Djokovic's ongoing saga, Elizabeth Holmes' conviction and the loss of Sidney Poitier.

column1: Opinion: Meet 18 people who think they know what will happen this year - CNN
column5: Which film will win the Oscar for best picture? Will Republicans trounce Democrats in the midterm elections? And what country will take home the most gold medals at the Beijing Winter Olympics?

column1: Opinion: Putin's war was launched on a runway of lies - CNN
column5: Frida Ghitis writes it is not the first time "big lies" have been spread by leaders. Russian President Vladimir Putin has used disinformation to justify and launch an unprovoked invasion of Ukraine.

column1: Opinion: President Zelensky is a profile in courage - CNN
column5: The brutal and wholly unjustified invasion of Ukraine has transfixed the world in horror, writes Jay Parini. And the heroic figure at the center of this war is none other than Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky.

column1: Opinion: What Trump's lavish praise of Putin reveals - CNN
column5: Michael D'Antonio says former President Donald Trump took the headline-grabbing route and declared Russian leader Vladimir Putin "very savvy" and his decision to roll his army into separatist-held parts of Ukraine "genius."

column1: I'd like to introduce you to the real Marilyn Monroe (opinion)  - CNN
column5: It's vanishingly difficult for Marilyn Monroe to be seen as an actual human being. Not after this many decades of being a symbol, a sex goddess, a blonde bombshell or a candle in the wind. As author Sarah Churchwell, whose book The Many Lives of Marilyn Monroe, has said, "What we think about Marilyn is what we think about women." In the 1950s, that proved to be a damning indictment.

column1: Opinion: A humble prediction for what comes after Omicron - CNN
column5: Almost two years into the Covid-19 pandemic, Dr. Kent Sepkowitz writes about what may lie ahead for a fatigued world that's battling the current Omicron wave. This latest variant, he says, should serve as a humbling lesson for infectious disease experts. The variant "broke every 'rule' of pandemic behavior we thought we had established." He adds, "My thinking is this: After four distinct surges, each with a lead viral variant, why would there not be five?" Living in this new abnormal, he says, we have to rely on, instead of predictions, what we know today while "doing our best to dodge whatever is coming at us."

column1: Opinion: San Francisco rape controversy will have a chilling effect - CNN
column5: If rape survivors believe that the evidence collected in their rape kits could be used against them, that's one more reason on an already-long list to not trust the criminal justice system -- or seek justice at all, argues Jill Filipovic.

column1: Opinion: California's endemic strategy is a vital step forward - CNN
column5: As we enter another year in which the pandemic is very much part of our lives, California's Covid-19 endemic framework is the only viable path forward, writes Julian Zelizer.

column1: Opinion: Beijing Olympics hit the heights -- and the depths - CNN
column5: Amy Bass writes about the Olympics as they draw to a close, framed by a Covid-19 pandemic, threats of war in Europe, and a doping scandal involving a 15-year-old skater.

column1: Opinion: Ukrainians are wondering if their comedian-turned-president can handle the world stage - CNN
column5: Michael Bociurkiw writes when Volodymyr Zelensky gave up his comedy career to jump into the world of Ukrainian politics, he could not have known within two years he'd become a president staring down thousands of Russian troops along his country's border. Now Ukrainians are wondering whether the showman is up to the job of wartime president.

column1:
Opinion: My Olympic figure skating dream came true. Don't let others get ruined
  - CNN
column5: To think that doping was happening under the nose of so many at the Olympics is deeply disturbing. I understand that standing up to Russia is complicated and hard, but for the IOC, their responsibility is clear, writes Canadian ice dancer Kaitlyn Weaver.

column1: Opinion: Why I'm scared about mask mandate rollbacks - CNN
column5: Kara Alaimo writes until vaccines are available to every American, ending mask mandates in public places is irresponsible and immoral. Doing so will endanger the health of young children and further drive parents to make impossible choices.

column1: Opinion: Canadian trucker protests are the latest example of Covid-19 absurdity - CNN
column5: What started out as a protest over Covid restrictions in Canada is now greatly disrupting peoples' everyday lives -- which is what the protest was supposedly aimed at stopping, writes Abdul El-Sayed

column1: Opinion: France is on a dangerous collision course with its Muslim population - CNN
column5: French lawmakers last month voted to ban women and girls from wearing hijab while playing sports -- showing the world that when it comes to further politicizing, targeting and policing European Muslim women, France is in a league of its own, writes Shaista Aziz.

column1: Opinion: What a NASA astronaut learned about working with Russians - CNN
column5: With tensions between the US and Russia at their highest level since the beginning of the International Space Station, it's worth looking to the skies for a way forward on Earth, writes American astronaut Leroy Chiao.

column1: Opinion: As Olympics begin, the world is looking. But will anyone be watching? - CNN
column5: As two Chinese athletes, one with roots in the minority Uyghur community, lit the cauldron to open the Winter Olympics in Beijing, the message from China to the rest of the world was clear, writes Amy Bass: These are our Olympics, not yours. Bass puts the ceremony in historical context and asks whether the joy and grit of competition will be enough to keep the world watching amid the anxieties sparked by China, Russia and the Covid-19 pandemic.

column1: Opinion: A pediatrician's advice for parents considering a potential Covid-19 vaccine for young kids - CNN
column5: New mom and pediatrician Edith Bracho-Sanchez reflects on the information -- like the high bar of safety and efficacy for clinical trials -- that helps her feel comfortable with the idea of vaccinating her baby when the time comes.

column1: Opinion: Why this modified pig heart transplant is a huge deal - CNN
column5: The news last week that David Bennett, a 57-year-old Maryland man, nearing death, had undergone cardiac transplant surgery with a genetically modified pig heart sent shock waves through the medical community, writes Dr. Jonathan Reiner.

column1: Opinion: I was a lawyer -- until the night I met Bob Saget - CNN
column5: Many people, especially comedians, have shared stories about Bob Saget's talent, kindness and support in the days following his death. For some, he was a father figure on "Full House." For others, he was their favorite comedian -- one with an unflinching sense of dark humor. But for Paul Farahvar, it was personal, he writes: Bob Saget literally changed the entire arc of his life.

column1: Opinion: Why China's Olympics matter to Putin - CNN
column5: Putin will likely think twice before overshadowing the Olympics (or at least the earlier part of it) and marring Xi Jinping's time to shine on the global stage. That's because Putin and Xi have become the world's autocracy bros, writes Frida Ghitis.

column1: Opinion: Pope Benedict XVI revelations are a chance to overhaul a rotten system - CNN
column5: During the last years of Benedict's reign, and further under Francis, many hoped for reforms and open dialogue led by the church. But with recent revelations, it is clear that the issues are as deep as the scars of the survivors, and we are yet to see a leader who is not afraid of the past, writes Matthias Katsch.

column1: Opinion: Jamie Oliver is veering into cultural appropriation. Because he's Jamie Oliver  - CNN
column5: The issue central to cultural appropriation is power. Therefore, no matter how many people Oliver is surrounded by, he is always going to be veering into the arena of cultural appropriation, writes Anna Sulan Masing.

column1: Australia's national day should be one of pride. Instead it commemorates an invasion: opinion - CNN
column5: January 26 marks the day the dispossession of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples began, and sets up European invasion as an important source of Australian identity and pride. In doing so, it ignores more than 60,000 years of pre-colonial history. As we approach the end of January 2022, many Australians are once again questioning why this date continues to be celebrated.

column1: Opinion: This is an unmistakable win for incarcerated people - CNN
column5: Michael Cohen, E. Danya Perry and Joshua Perry write that __he Federal Bureau of Prisons announced that it will finally implement a key justice reform promise made in 2018's First Step Act, but one which the prior administration had been far too slow to carry out.

column1: Opinion: The future of the GOP isn't about Ron DeSantis or Glenn Youngkin - CNN
column5: As debates continue about the Republican Party's post-Trump future, it will be critical to see past conventional political labels -- lest they conceal the true threats imperiling American democracy, writes Nicole Hemmer. The tendency to see the Republican Party as a body organized by a split between moderates and conservatives goes back decades, but today, those labels fail to capture the party's truth, she argues.

column1: Opinion: America has taken its eyes off the ball on Iran  - CNN
column5: David A. Andelman writes that the noise surrounding Russia's "drumbeat of war" against Ukraine has obscured another pressing security issue: Iran's nuclear capabilities. Experts warn that Iran may be within months of having the technology to manufacture nuclear weapons -- whether they do or not ultimately remains to be seen.

column1: What it will take to save American democracy - CNN
column5: More than a year after the January 6 riot at the US Capitol, CNN's Fareed Zakaria writes that American democracy is still under threat -- but we can do something about it.

column1: Opinion: Kevin McCarthy's comment is a warning sign - CNN
column5: Jill Filipovic writes that Kevin McCarthy's comments about stripping certain Democrats of committee assignments should the GOP win in midterms is yet another warning sign that Republicans are on a path to becoming an antidemocratic party.

column1: Opinion: The text message I sent my wife inside the Capitol - CNN
column5: Rep. Colin Allred writes that, on January 6, the most important thing that happened was not a failed attempt to reject the results of a free, fair and secure election, but Congress acting in a strong bipartisan fashion to reaffirm our democracy later that night.

column1: Opinion: The Bronx fire brings back memories of 'screaming faces at the windows' of Grenfell - CNN
column5: Watching the news footage of the fatal fire that spread through a New York apartment block Sunday, Yvette Williams writes that she was transported back in time to another fire that four years ago changed her life forever.

column1: Opinion: These Supreme Court arguments are about far more than vaccine mandates - CNN
column5: Jennifer Rodgers writes that the US Supreme Court oral arguments over federal Covid-19 vaccine mandates could foreshadow the conservative majority's view of executive power: specifically, how much control the federal government has over rule-making.

column1: Pig heart transplant: Man with terminal heart disease gets a transplant of genetically modified organ - CNN
column5: A 57-year-old Maryland man is doing well three days after receiving a genetically modified pig heart in a first-of-its-kind transplant surgery, University of Maryland Medicine said in a news release Monday.

column1: Kane Tanaka, the world's oldest living person, turns 119  - CNN
column5: Kane Tanaka, the world's oldest living person, turned 119 years old on Sunday, according to a Twitter post published by her great-granddaughter, Junko Tanaka.

column1: Nixon China visit: Fifty years later, questions hang over the US-China future - CNN
column5: When US President Richard Nixon walked down the red-carpeted stairs from Air Force One to shake hands with Chinese Premier Zhou Enlai on a cold day in Beijing on February 21, 1972, it was hailed by many as a world-changing gesture.

column1: El Clasico: Barcelona humiliates Real Madrid to signal return of form for club in recovery  - CNN
column5: It wasn't long ago that Barcelona was a club in crisis.

column1: Kaillie Humphries: World's top female bobsledder says she switched to US team after fearing for her 'physical safety' - CNN
column5: Any time Kaillie Humphries wishes, the world's top female bobsledder can gaze into the mirror and look back on her remarkable career; the artwork that adorns most of her body reminds her of the whole story.
